,Recommended,259570,20150249,"Posted: 31 December, 2015",all,Franky,"To say that there are a fair number of ""crafting survival"" games these days would be a dramatic understatement. It seems like nary a week goes by without a handful more hitting Steam, let alone other platforms. And yet, Eden Star is proof positive that there is still a lot of room for different, novel ideas to take root in a genre becoming increasingly crowded.It's highly likely that you've played this kind of game a thousand times before now. Start with nothing. Forage stuff. Build stuff. Survive the night. Forage better stuff. Survive the increasingly difficult nights. And so on. The basic gameplay loop hasn't fundamentally changed from what Minecraft established years ago.Where Eden Star differentiates itself is two fold: one, its sci fi skin actually proves to be pretty compelling, as both the bases, defences, and weaponry you have at your disposal genuinely feel rewarding. There's inklings of Mass Effect and Deus Ex here in everything from the weapon design to the way the ""magic"" feels. The core gameplay here is rock solid.More importantly, though, Eden Star differentiates itself by way of its developers. Early access games are hard to get right, and Eden Star is helmed by a crew who is deadset on staying active in the community. The Trello Board is updated frequently, and the communicativeness of their planning and execution makes this one Early Access title you shouldn't be afraid of.Plus, having just patched in an entire multiplayer mode right before the holidays, it's clear the crew is dedicated to their game.Ultimately, though, both of these differentiating factors wouldn't matter if the game wasn't fun to play, and it is. More content will only help Eden Star become an even better, more widely adopted and successful game than it already is.Here's to that future success."
,Recommended,259570,33790350,Posted: 25 July,all,Tekkarath,"This is an amazing framework to build on for the future, the building and crafting systems are pretty solid.  But more importantly the movement system is amazing, I first realized there was more to movement in this game when I ran from the initial starting point to the first base you're led to.  It was dark, I didn't know how to activate the personal light (It's L I just hadn't tried it yet) and I ran headfirst into a tree.  Before I could strafe I had run into it, and then something strange happened, I seemed to runupthe tree.Well it was dark and I was being chased so I chalked it up to pre-alpha, new game, whatever.  But after I'd survived the night and had some time to play around with the game without being attacked, I realized that If I ran at vertical objects I could run up them a bit.  Tapping the jump button when I was close to an edge after running up a wall allowed me to grab the edge and pull myself up (You can also climb half walls by tapping jump next to them), it took some getting used to but after some practice I can scale two or three story buildings as long as there are handholds of some kind (windows, half walls).  Not to mention the wall running, which If I were the type to build a free-running obstacle course with the in-game building system (I'm not, but maybe if I get bored enough) I could probably waste another twenty or so hours on that alone.Now I've played Mirror's Edge so I wasn't new to games with excellent movement, but I just wasn't expecting it in a pre-alpha game marketed as a building/survival type.The building is pretty easy, and bit more detailed than most games in which you can build freely in an open world.  Foundations, walls, fortifications, ceilings  are your starting point, add half walls, doorways etc. to taste but if you build too big you'll need to use support beams to hold up your floor.  The added realism of needing proper support for larger buildings also plays a part in the 'destroy' part of the game, since you could bring down a significant portion of a building by attacking the foundation or beams.  There may not be anything currently implemented that powerful (Explosives, missiles, other high tech future stuff), but the potential is there.Destroying things can be pretty satisfying, your building tool also doubles as a 'grabber' for wildlife and some enemies, and slinging the mouse in any direction will fling the offending object out of your way, and possibly into nearby rocks or trees.  If it's your kind of thing just walking around gobbling down rocks and trees for materials is a good way to waste an in-game day, if it isn't your thing you can change how fast you gather materials or how much material is recieved from each item destroyed.  Most nights you'll be holed up in base keeping your things from being destroyed, healing walls and turrets, or possibly just watching the carnage unfold from your personal observation deck if your defenses are good enough.The enemies aren't too terribly smart, but their types reflect how they act.  Bug-types, swarm and overwhelm mostly, there are a couple other types, but nothing smart enough to get through a well-made defense.  There's a very Starship Troopers feel to defending your base sometimes, but nowhere near the sense of dread since the enemies mostly mill about the ground attacking your doors and getting chewed up by your turrets, there are some flying enemies, but if you keep your turrets upgraded they aren't too large a threat.  Having some enemies to scale walls and attack turrets or doors on the top of your base, or maybe some that could slip in through windows to attack power supplies.Currently at what I assume is 'endgame' tech (fully upgraded eden kit, multiple level three turrets, two weapons with tons of ammo), surviving the night feels like being a lone Marine in a well defended base facing a really poorly timed zerg rush, I feel like if they all came at once I wouldn't stand much of a chance, but they're staggered enough that my turrets wipe them out in droves.But there are certainly worse complaints to have about a pre-alpha game than 'It feels like Starship Troopers or Starcraft sans the Protoss but I'm not dying enough' so even if these guys go belly up tomorrow and this is what I'm left with to play I still consider it money well spent."
