,Recommended,259570,19893484,"Posted: 23 December, 2015",all,Cakemoth,"Starts out gathering resources, Looses base. Figures out I have a way of finding my base, goes out to explore and almost dies. Forgets I have a way to find base, wanders and gets lost, returns to base - night one begins. One enemy... I think this game is to ez pez. Night two, Army of xenos comes and I get rekt.20/10 epic game, great building system so far and so much potentialIt's time for another update! - 6/29/2017Honestly, I don't have that much time in the game (In fact, I havent touched it much within this year). Though I can say, the progress that the Dev's are putting out on this game is phenomenal. There are progress updates, and teasers of what to come frequently. Including, the gameplay so far has gotten better.[SPOILER ALERT]The Map has been updated,there are preset bases to compete with (They do not have their own AI enemies that operate like the player) however, they have turrets, and they will fire back at you.The map itself is considerably larger, INCREDIBLY larger. Not only this, there are a multitude of new/different areas to make your base.Combat is overall, the same - gathering resources is no different either.All in all, the game is progressing greatly, gameplay still continues to be smooth, though with many things added on the map, ES is also starting to gain a bit of a story. Would still reccomend this game, as the developers seem to be active to both the community, and to the games development.- - - - -Updated Review 2/28/2016Now-  serious part of the review. (MANY MANY run on sentences)Seeing as, I don't have so many hours in this game - That doesn't make someone bad whatsoever. Eden-Star is that type of game where you arent judged by how good you are in hours put into the game, The game is relativley very easy to pick up, where the hours would only mean how large someones base could possibly be. In four hours, I have achieved most things (Some things i dont like to unlock) - this is not including weapons. This game is very free-to-do on your own basis, as in it has no meta.I'll break it down with some points on how free you are from many things.Combat System -With the combat system, in most games that involve survival, you'd have to use a ""main"" tier of weapon, primarily relying on a gun, or some sort of other system. In Eden-Star, you can obtain the Energy Blade relativley early (Basically a superbuffed version of a wrist baton) ; with the addon of automatic aim for melee, you have the capability of charging air enemies, and in basic, warp jumping and smashing them out of the sky (It's not a one hit kill most of the time). Including, you cant just sweep and expect to kill everything, the melee system is Voxel-Physics based, If i were to hit something they could possibly tumble and slightly damage other enemies around them, the blade slicing from the main enemy into the next one besides it. Not only this, due to the physics/voxel way of the game, you have the capability of shoving things down hills or off cliffs.(A quick note) RMD Modules -Laser hand! Be Iron-man!Use the force to litteraly smash explosive cysts onto your enemies, or smash them into walls, other enemies, throw them in the sky, etc! (Some enemies explode on death, though they have a start up timer to that, you can throw corpses away or into other enemies!)Gauss cannon! Because whatevers in your face is going to die.With guns, The different types of weapons you have in Eden-Star have the capability of using any of them as a main weapon, as they are all realistically powerful; though are able to be played for people with different playstyles, riflemen, bullet spazzing-smg players, or snipers.Building -Since the world is voxel based, If you play Space Engineers you can get a feel for how it all works. Though with that, you can mesh things together (Like in Medieval Engineers) ; If you play Ark Survival Evolved, you may also get this concept. If you place one foundation, you can place walls on all four sides, then on the outer part of those walls, and below into the floor covering the foundation itself (Sometimes you cant, as it runs into voxels which balances it; though for the most part you have very free basis to add even more armor to foundations with this feature). In short, if that confused you, One foundation can hold 12 walls (Which is very cheap) - leaving bases able to be very cheap to create. The game also has a bit of 'structural integrity', platforms only go so far without having a support beam under them (Which can be covered with eight walls on one platform) - as real physics dictates, if that beam breaks, you can be sure whatever ontop of it will go down with it - sadly you wont get the resources from whatever broke. Turrets are automated and for the stages of this game, GREATLY work. They cover a bit of angles, and don't fire directly into your base, or try to fire if somethings inside, breaking your own stuff. Not only this, Since the game is voxel based, you could have turrets wherever you want, they are not limited to platforms, or foundations. You can have half walls out on the fields as well, not limiting it to just platforms/foundations.- The only thing with building is that it can only get a certain extent from your EDEN-Kit (3x3 Square Core you need to protect, loosing this does not end the game) ; This ONLY applies to what i know, solid big mass buildings, you can freely place other foundations/EDEN Kits and whatnot inside/around your EDEN-Kit's bubble (Expandable). Not only this - Buildings, are VERY. VERY. Tough. (Since i use Ironite, very common)"
