76561198078773953,Recommended,259570,33717929,Posted: 22 July,all,hotspur59,"IMO this is the best game in the currently popular genre of alien planet/sci fi, open world/sandbox, crafting and combat games. We are told more of a storyline will follow.The UI is intuitive and easy to use, the graphics are top notch, the game even in early development is balanced and plays pretty well, the planet is cool, there is many and varied flora and fauna, some cuddly some not so! You have access to underwater gathering, and dangers too. You can craft and construct many and varied things, but rightly some items are hard to find and dangerous to access.For me what makes it top notch is the way they've handled the daily grind - no axe, hatchet or worktool here, but instead a unique device set in your RH glove that draws materials in via a ""laser type"" beam. The big bonus of this device is you can also pick up any living creature within the beam by holding down your mouse button, and hurl it to oblivion, if you don't have time, or want to switch to your kinectic shotgun to save the precious ammo. Currenty my distance record is clear across a lake!The start is suitably challenging and you'll likely die a few times before you get your base defences up and running. I did.There is an annoying but realistic liklihood that whilst your taking a rest and quenching your thirst via the inventory, some or deep in resource gathering, some alien beastie is likely biting into your ankle! You will lose health and suffer damage to your suit, also gain infections from such encounters.Unlike the now excellent No Man's Sky and Empyrion, there is currently only one planet to play about on in Eden Star, so the flora and fauna does get a bit repetitive over time. Hopefully the devs will expand on this in the future, because for me this one currently plays the best. Would be nice say if the planet had a darker and hareder side for example.On the whole highly recomended even in early access. The  devs are very responsive and enthusiastic too."
